title: For Sale/Trade:  Beretta 1934, Brescia Late WWII, .380 G prefix, Polished blank slide
location: Fort Thomas, Kentucky near Cincinnati, Northern Kentucky, Kentucky
postcontent: If you can see this ad, the gun is still available.  I will cancel when sold. A nice Beretta Model 1934, in 9 mm Corto (Browning short), blank slide G prifx, Brescia plant.  The standard issue sidearm of the Italian Army in WWII.  The high polish, blank slide pistols were made during that period where Mussolini had been deposed and before the German's took over complete control of the Beretta plant.  Probably among the pistols known to have been issued to the Italian RSI (Socialist Republic) and the German occupation forces. Only produced in 1944. The slide was left blank because the nature of the incoming government was in question; after the German's took over the Beretta plants, the finish became significantly less well finished--rough, mill marks, etc., and a left side, slide legend was restored.  No issues, problems, etc.

title: For Sale:  Guns for good prices
postcontent:
The Bersa Thunder .380, for those unaware, is a Walther PPK clone. Though it's not an exact copy, it's incredibly close. For those also unaware, the the PPK is one of the most popular and enduring CCW pistol designs in existence, having been in production since 1929.
But the .380 isn't a 9mm, you might object. No, it's not, but a subcompact pistol is meant to be used up close and personal, and the .380 Auto cartridge is very serviceable with the right load at close range.
This pistol uses a DA/SA mechanism, so it will require one to learn the intricacies of the double-action trigger system. The safety is a pin block/decocker, so cocked and locked carry won't be possible. That said, it's a proven design and a very popular deep concealment pistol. They're in most gun stores and the Matte Finish model, the most basic of them all, can be had quite frequently for $1000. If that isn't a slam dunk...nothing is
